    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Achillea millefolium improperly include triggering seizures in individuals with photosensitive epilepsy due to its high content of sesquiterpene lactones, which can cause phototoxicity. Additionally, some people may experience an allergic reaction to the plant's bioactive compounds, resulting in symptoms such as hives, itching, and difficulty breathing. Achillea millefolium may also interact with blood thinners, such as warfarin, and cause an increased risk of bleeding, due to its ability to inhibit platelet aggregation. Long-term use of the plant has been linked to liver damage, likely caused by its hepatotoxic compounds, which can lead to elevated liver enzymes and liver failure in severe cases. Furthermore, Achillea millefolium may interact with certain medications, such as diuretics and blood pressure medications, which can lead to adverse effects, including hypotension and electrolyte imbalances."
